Phase 6 Part 9 - Final QA: performance audit re-pass over Parts 4-8

Part 3 (docs/phase-6-part3-performance.md) already covered database
indexes/API performance/React rendering/lazy loading/image optimization/
caching/compression for the whole system through Part 2. This pass
re-examined Parts 4-8's additions specifically for new performance
concerns.

Reviewed, no issues found:
- metrics.ts (Part 4): recordRequest() is O(number of histogram buckets)
  = O(10) per request, all in-memory Map operations -- negligible
  overhead added to the request path, verified functionally correct in
  Part 4's standalone test (6/6 checks) and re-verified this pass to
  confirm no behavior change from the Part 9 timingSafeEqual fix (which
  only touched metrics.routes.ts's auth check, not metrics.ts itself).
- SentryErrorTracker (Part 4): fire-and-forget `fetch(...).catch(...)`,
  never awaited by errorHandler.ts -- a slow or unreachable Sentry
  endpoint cannot add latency to any actual HTTP response.
- Backup scripts (Part 5): run out-of-band (cron/CI), never on the
  request-serving path -- no application performance impact by
  construction.
- CI/CD (Part 6): build-and-push already uses cache-from/cache-to:
  type=gha for both Docker image builds, meaningfully speeding up repeat
  CI runs; not applicable to runtime app performance.
- Mobile assets (Part 7): app icons/splash generated at reasonable file
  sizes for their purpose (512px icon: 5KB, maskable 512px: 11KB, 2732px
  splash: 51KB) -- none large enough to be a real bundle-size or load-time
  concern, and none of them ship in the web bundle anyway (icons load
  directly as static files; the mobile-assets/ source images are only
  consumed by the native build process, never fetched by a browser).
- Service worker (Part 7): cache-first strategy for the Vite-hashed
  bundle reduces repeat-visit load time (no re-fetch of unchanged JS/CSS);
  confirmed in Part 7's standalone test that this never applies to
  API responses, so it cannot serve stale data in exchange for that
  speed.

No new performance issues found or fixed in this pass -- Parts 4-8 are
observability/ops/mobile/documentation work, not request-path code, so
this is a plausible and expected outcome rather than an incomplete audit.
